    <section class="main-section" id="Some_Hacking_Tools">

      <header>
        <h1>Some Hacking Tools</h1>
      </header>
      <code>
      <div>
        <h1>Nmap</h1>
        <h1> Purpose:</h1>

        <p>Nmap is primarily used for network discovery and security auditing. It helps in mapping out networks,
          identifying</p> <br>
        <p> what devices are running on them, and discovering the services those devices are offering.</p>
        Typical Uses:

        <ol>
          <li>Network Inventory:<br>
       Identifying what devices are on a network.</li>
          <li> Open Ports and Services: <br>
      Discovering open ports and the services running on them.</li>
          <li>Operating System Detection:<br>
       Determining the OS and versions running on networked devices.</li>
          <li> Vulnerability Detection: <br>
     Identifying vulnerable services and configurations.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>


      <div>
        <h1>Metasploit</h1>
        <p>Metasploit is a framework for developing, testing, and executing exploit code against a remote target
          machine.
          It’s widely used for penetration testing and security research.</p>

        <h1> Typical Uses:</h1>

        <ol>
          <li>Exploit Development: <br>
          Creating and customizing exploits.</li>

          <li>Payload Delivery: <br>
        Delivering payloads to compromised systems.</li>

          <li>Post-Exploitation:<br>
       Performing actions on compromised systems to gather further information or to maintain control.</li>

          <li>Vulnerability Assessment:<br>
      Testing the effectiveness of security measures.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
</code>
    </section>

    <section class="main-section" id="Some_Hacking_Techniques">

      <header>
        <h1>Some Hacking Techniques<h1>
      </header>
      <code>
      <div>
         <h1>SQL Injection</h1>
          <p>SQL Injection is a code injection technique that exploits a vulnerability in an application’s software by
            manipulating SQL queries made to a database. An attacker can insert or "inject" malicious SQL code into a
            query,
            allowing them to retrieve, alter, or delete data.</p>
          <span>
      <h1>Typical Uses:</h1>

      <p>
        <a>Data Theft:</a> Extracting sensitive information from the database.<br>
        <a>Data Manipulation:</a> Modifying or deleting data within the database.<br>
        <a>Authentication Bypass:</a> Logging into applications without proper credentials.<br>
        <a>Database Corruption:</a> Damaging or corrupting database records.<br>
      </p>
      </span>

          <span>
        <h1>Prevention:</h1>

      <p><a>Use Prepared Statements (Parameterized Queries):</a> Ensures that user input is treated as data, not executable code.<br>
      <a>Input Validation:</a> Validate and sanitize all user inputs.<br>
      <a>Least Privilege:</a> Ensure the database account used by the application has the least privileges necessary.</p>
      
      </span>
      </div>
      <span>
        <h1>Types:</h1>

      <p><a href="">Stored XSS:</a> Malicious script is stored on the server (e.g., in a database) and served to users.<br>
      <a href="">Reflected XSS:</a>Malicious script is reflected off a web server, such as in an error message or search result.<br>
      <a href="">DOM-based XSS:</a> The vulnerability exists in the client-side code rather than the server-side.<br></p>
      </span>

      <h1> Prevention:</h1>

      <ol>
        <li>Input Sanitization:
          Remove or escape potentially dangerous characters.</li><br>
        <li>Output Encoding:
          Encode data before rendering it in the browser (e.g., HTML encoding).</li><br>
        <li>Content Security Policy (CSP):
          Implement a CSP to restrict the sources from which content can be loaded.</li><br>
      </ol>
      </code>
    </section>

